His state recently equipped 500 cars with tachographs to test a mile based payment system.
“ This is the best alternative in the long run, ” he said.
Bureaucrats call it a mileage based user charge.
Not surprisingly, the idea appeals to urban liberals, because the tax could be used, for example, to influence driving behaviour in such a way that reduces congestion and climate-damaging emissions.
California ’ s planners rely on the system to devise strategies to achieve the state ’ s ambitious, legally binding climate change goals.
But the Pennsylvania Republican Bill Shuster, Chairman of the House Transportation Committee, has also declared that he sees this as the most viable long-term alternative.
The Reason Foundation ’ s free marketers also embrace the idea of making drivers pay by distance travelled.
“ This is not a tax that disappears into a black hole, ” explains Adrian Moore, Vice President of Guidelines at Reason.
People are paying directly for what they are getting.
The movement is also supported by two former US transport ministers who, in a 2011 report, called on Congress to move toward mileage accounting.
The US Senate approved a $90 million pilot last year, covering 10,000 cars.
But the majority in the House of Representatives prevented the move, responding to the concerns of rural MEPs who represent people who often have to travel many miles to work or to the city in their daily lives.
Nevertheless, several states and cities are moving in this direction on their own.
Most committed is Oregon, who currently recruits 5,000 drivers for the country ’ s largest experiment.
These drivers will soon pay mileage fees to the state instead of the petroleum tax.
Nevada has already completed a pilot project.
New York City is also considering such a thing.
Illinois tests it to a limited extent with trucks.
And the I-95 Coalition, which includes the transport ministries of 17 states on the east coast (including Maryland, Pennsylvania, Virginia, and Florida), is currently examining how the change could be introduced.
The concept is not universal.
In Nevada, where 50 volunteers were recently equipped with equipment, drivers were skeptical about thinking that the government could follow any of their movements.
“ Concerns about Big Brother and such things were a major problem, ” explains Alauddin Khan, Head of Strategic and Outcome Management at the Nevada Ministry of Transport.
People did not want.
When the test started, Nevada ACLU warned on its Web site: “ It would be relatively easy to turn tachographs into fully-fledged surveillance devices. ”
There is no need to build a gigantic, bulky technological infrastructure that would inevitably be used to collect data on the daily movements of individuals.
Nevada is one of a number of states that are now looking for affordable technology that will allow the state to capture the kilometers travelled, but not exactly when and where.
According to Khan, this would also reassure public opinion.
The hunt for this technology has led some authorities to a small start-up company called True Mileage in California.
The company did not originally step in to help states tax drivers.
Rather, its aim was to gain a foothold in an emerging market for motor insurance, where drivers are to pay on the basis of the miles they have travelled.
But the equipment she tests is also of interest to road planners, because they do not work with GPS and provide limited information that is regularly uploaded via modem.
“ People are more willing to participate if their speed and locations are not recorded, ” said Ryan Morrison, Chief Executive Officer of True Mileage.
Major mistakes were made in some of these public pilot programmes.
There are much cheaper and less intrusive ways in which this is implemented.
In Oregon, planners experiment with giving drivers a variety of choices.
You can choose with or without GPS.
Or they do not choose any equipment at all and instead pay a flat rate based on the average mileage travelled by all state residents.
Other bodies hope to sell the concept of a distrustful public sphere by providing the devices with more functions than fewer ones.
In New York City, transport officials want to develop a tax device that can also pay parking fees, pay insurance only for mileage travelled, and collect speed data in real time from other vehicles that will enable drivers to avoid congestion.
“ Drivers would be motivated to participate by the added value of the benefits offered by the system, ” says one of the city ’ s planning documents.
But some traffic planners wonder whether all the talk about paying per mile is not just a huge distraction.
At the Metropolitan Transportation Commission for the San Francisco Bay area, officials declared that Congress could solve the bankrupt Highway Trust Fund simply by raising the fuel tax.
An additional one-off fee or annual levy could be imposed on hybrid vehicles or other vehicles that consume little petrol, so that they, too, pay a fair share.
