Esa decides on major space missions: missions for billions
Far planets, gravitational waves or black holes - experts from the European Space Agency must now agree on two major projects that they intend to launch in the coming years.
There were 30 proposals to choose from, five of which are still in the race.
Far away worlds.
Astronomers have already found more than 1000 planets in other stars.
No one knows whether there are lives on at least some of them.
The choice is difficult: search for gravitational waves?
Or rather explore the origin of the cosmos?
Or search for earth-like planets and thus perhaps discover alien life?
These questions are being asked by those responsible for the European Space Agency Esa.
For their Cosmic Vision programme, they are looking for ideas for two major space projects that should make decisive progress in research.
The budget for such L missions is around EUR 1 billion.
The launch is expected to take place in 2028 and 2034.
In early September, the elite of European space research met in Paris to discuss proposals for such missions.
Thirty ideas were discussed, five of which have now been shortlisted.
Many bodies are looking at the proposals and researchers are lagging behind.
A final decision is to be taken by the Scientific Programme Committee in the next few days.
The Esa has selected a total of four major questions, to which the missions of the Cosmic Vision programme, initiated in 2007, will find answers.
What are the conditions for the formation of planet and life?
The exact process of creating stars from large gas clouds - and thus the formation of planets that orbit these stars - are still in the proverbial darkness.
A large infrared telescope in space could permeate through this darkness.
And if a star has a planet, under what circumstances can life be created there?
To investigate this question, the " Cheops " space telescope is to be launched in 2017, which will examine in closely 500 already known planetary systems in our vicinity.
But the possibilities are limited, cheops is a small mission with a budget of 150 million euros.
With larger instruments, astronomers could map earth-like planets, and even analyze the composition of their atmospheres, thus searching for " biomarkers ": gases that are seen as an indication of biological activity.
How does solar work?
This question, too, should ultimately shed light on the conditions that exist for the creation of life.
The magnetic activity of a star and the interaction of its magnetic field as well as its particle radiation with the planetary system play an important role.
These processes can be examined as examples in our solar system.
With the Solar Orbiter, the Esa has already approved an M class mission (the budget is about half a billion euros) for this issue.
The probe starts in 2017 and closely observe the surface and activity of the sun.
Jupiter and its moons are also of great interest to researchers.
They want to find out what role the giant planet played in the development of the solar system.
The Esa is the first of the three L missions of the Cosmic Vision program.
The probe " Juice " (Jupiter Icy Moons Explorer) is expected to start its journey in 2022.
She reached Jupiter eight years later and was to investigate the atmosphere of the planet as well as the icy moons of Europe, Kallisto and Ganymed.
What are the basic physical laws of the universe?
Space space offers many opportunities to study matter under extreme conditions and thus to examine whether the laws of nature with which we are familiar are still valid there.
There may also be deviations that could show physicists the way to a new theory under whose umbrella all known laws of nature can be combined.
How did the universe come into being, and what does it consist of?
13.7 billion years ago, our cosmos were created by the Big Bang.
In addition to the familiar matter that make up stars, planets, and creatures like us, there are dark matter whose gravity holds galaxies and clusters of galaxies together, and dark energy that accelerates the expansion of space.
So far, researchers do not know which physical laws were valid in the first fractions of the big Bang ’ s second, nor do they know what dark matter and dark energy consist of.
With " Euclid ", the Esa has already approved an M mission to be launched in 2020.
By means of a special telescope, the probe is to examine the distribution of matter in the universe for the first time in the entire sky, thus enabling conclusions to be drawn as to the nature of dark matter and dark energy.
Who Could Make the Race
Of the 30, only two will remain at the end of the selection process.
According to many experts, the best chances for an L-mission are " E-Lisa ", an ambitious concept for detecting gravitational waves.
By this physicists mean changes in the structure of spacetime that Albert Einstein predicted almost 100 years ago.
They have not been proven.
Elisa could succeed, scientists hope behind the project.
The mission provided for a detector consisting of two or three probes, which was stationed in space.
Unlike plants on Earth, it could also detect gravitational waves created by the Big Bang, thus providing new insights into the emergence of the cosmos.
Four other proposals compete for the second L mission: a large X-ray telescope called " Athena " to explore black holes, " Icy Planets ", another mission to the outer planets of the solar system, " Prism ", a cosmic background radiation measurement mission, and the " Exoplanet Finder " to detect and investigate earth-like planets.
Proposals for the retransport of samples from Mars, moon, Venus and asteroid exploration, and solar physics have already left.
