Two investigators followed the suspect and saw him go to Ditta's house where he put the drugs under the lawyer's dustbin with 60% purity in a black golf glove.
Shortly after delivering the drugs, Scarborough regularly telephoned Ditta, who was in the Blackburn Rovers football stadium in Ewood Park for dinner.
The lawyer returned home, got the drugs and then nine communications were exchanged between them.
It became known in court that Ditta was a “ regular consumer ” of cocaine after tests had discovered Class A drugs in his hair, wallets, and credit cards.
Ditta was later arrested, but refused to take cocaine and said that he had talked to the alleged dealer because he was his client, claiming that her discussion was subject to “ lawyers ’ secrecy. ”
