What happens to my email en route?
E-mail is actually called an electronic letter.
Has e-mail technically implemented postal secrecy in the design of the Internet service, in the same way as conventional postal services?
In the conception of early Internet services, the focus was on making communication possible.
That is why the basic technical protocols have failed to provide a solid basis for correspondence.
As a result, a conventional e-mail is more like an open postcard than a sealed letter.
If the user sends a mail " Anna " to " Benni ", are the computers of the two directly connected?
The first step of Anna's e-mail program or browser sends the mail to the mail server of her service provider.
For example, if it has a mail account, that would be Google.
This mail server sends content to the provider using Benni.
On the route, the mail can run via a number of other servers on the Internet.
Bennie can then call the content from his / her provider.
Are conventional e-mails on their way through the net?
Most mails are read several times on the way by software robots.
The sender's provider usually checks whether the mail is accompanied by a malicious program as an attachment.
A virus check is also carried out on the receiver systems.
In addition, providers check whether this is an annoying and unsolicited spam mail that is immediately deleted or at least sorted away into a spam folder.
Do robots have another task?
On systems like GMail, the robot also determines the information Google needs to place context advertising.
If Anna and Benni communicate via GMail about their upcoming holiday trip, Google may display links to holiday offers.
Do unknown people also read the emails?
The likelihood that unauthorized people will read a mail is extremely slim.
Theoretically, however, this is possible.
In companies, administrators often have the opportunity to read e-mail.
The law enforcement authorities and the secret services also have legal opportunities to intercept or take note of e-mails.
In addition, there are possible illegal spying.
Is it possible to protect e-mails against reading?
With encryption according to the OpenPGP standard, an e-mail can be effectively encrypted against reading.
With great technical effort it is also possible to hide the metadata of an e-mail communication, so that it is not easy to identify who communicated with whom.
How important are Yahoo and Google in the e-mail market in Germany?
According to an investigation by Convios Consulting in August 2013, Yahoo and Google play only a minor role in the mainly privately used mailboxes.
While the shares of Yahoo Mail had recently fallen, GMail from Google was able to increase significantly.
