George Kerevan: European Unbundling Gives the Scots Choice
A new day, a new story of independence.
This time we are warned that an independent Scotland is needed to join the Schengen area as a condition for EU membership.
This provides the keyword for stories about passport controls in Berwick and a barbed wire border along the Hadrian Wall.
Indeed, the Strathclyde proposal highlighted the potential economic benefits that more freedom to travel would bring to the rest of Europe, but this did not matter in the headlines, as expected.
Nor has anyone mentioned that EU member states often bend their strict rules when it is more favourable to them.
As Scotland is not currently part of the Schengen area, continued disregard for Brussels would be a small concession in exchange for what they really want from the Scots.
So not really a story.
And one that has already come over the years that it already resembles a fossil: for the first time I heard the “ independence means passport control ” duck at least 40 years ago.
An interesting point is lost in the constant repetition of this ancient saga.
Why expect an independent Scotland to dance to European tune?
Why exchange the London yoke for the yoke of Brussels, especially now?
That is the real European news: the great post-war plan for the unification of Europe has stalled.
The European project officially died with the euro crisis.
Parties are gaining ground across the EU that are anti-EU or that want to abandon the euro as a common currency.
Even in Germany, the Euroskeptic Alternative for Germany Party – founded only this year – was able to win just under five million votes in the September federal election, effectively evicting the Free Democrats (the equivalent of the British Liberal Democrats) from the Bundestag.
There has always been opposition to the plan to create a federal Europe.
But the current economic crisis turns out to be a turning point.
Many people believe that the European project has gone too far because of the strict austerity policies imposed by Berlin and the European Central Bank, linked with the straitjacket into which the national economy is forced by adherence to the single currency.
The euro ’ s crisis has little to do with the fact that national governments are causing excessive budget deficits – and only in Greece.
Instead, the euro system has nailed its members into exchange rates that benefit German exporters – and that is what German politicians would like to leave.
Without the possibility of depreciation of the local currency, southern Europe finds itself at a built-in productivity disadvantage vis-à-vis Germany.
The only way forward is to cut wages and public spending – spurred on by Berlin.
Behind the current budgetary and monetary problems there is a deeper European productivity problem.
As a result of the “ green ” energy directives imposed by Brussels – a code for subsidizing French and German energy companies at the expense of consumers – European industry pays twice as much electricity as four times the United States.
This is a crialysing cost disadvantage, as we saw in Grangemouth.
All wage world's wage limits do not protect the European petrochemical industry from being sidelined by cheap American shale gas.
As a result, a revolt is emerging, especially in France, the EU's former cheerleader.
After the war, France ’ s political elite saw the EU as a vehicle for containing Germany and putting Paris on an equal footing with Washington.
But Berlin no longer needs Paris as a gateway to political legitimacy, and Europe has imposed its own economic policy, which is what the battered French economy has to contend with.
The result: Marine Le Pen ’ s right-wing, anti-EU National Front has just won a decisive by-election, relegating the ruling Socialists to third place.
The National Front is now the most popular party in France, with 24% of the vote – a timely warning to the British Labour Party that it cannot assume that division on the right will automatically benefit the left.
What does Le Pen do with its newfound popularity among working-class white French?
It wants to use next year's EU elections to forge an anti-EU anti-currency bloc in the European Parliament.
If the anti-EU parties do well in these elections – and this is perfectly possible – then such a bloc could dominate the European Parliament for the first time.
This is the point I would like to make: in the not-too-distant future, growing resentment of the EU and the single currency will come together to abolish the euro.
The EU will not disappear, but it will become something more like the “ Europe of (sovereign) nations ” favored by General de Gaulle.
Germany and a few of its satellite economies may hold fast to the euro, but France and southern Europe will return to their own currencies.
I expect the UK to distance itself from this project in the hope of flattering itself with the United States.
But Washington ’ s growing interest in the Pacific region suggests that Britain will be alone in the Atlantic rain.
What has happened to Scotland in all this?
We can decide to be a region of (in the final analysis) Lesser England.
Or we can defend our own economic interests – including telling Berlin and Brussels what they can get stuck in and where.
I suspect that Scotland could do very well in a looser European grouping, provided that we retain our own currency.
Cooperation with other similar countries is easier in a non-federal Europe of nations.
Otherwise, we should consider doing the same and maintaining our economic independence.
The SNP government in Scotland is, remarkably – the most successful anti-austerity political movement in Europe and won a spectacular majority in 2011, owing to the rejection of the proposed (and made) cuts that Labour Chancellor of the Exchequer Alistair Darling and the subsequent Tory Lib Dem-Coalition were responsible for.
It would be ridiculous for Scotland to opt for independence now only to get austerity imposed by Berlin and Brussels.
