Pfandhouses are booming in Singapore because the crisis has arrived in the middle class.
In a deposit house in the Bendemeer shopping mall in Singapore, Janani Amirthalinga swaps a golden bracelet, a ring, and a pair of earrings to pay her daughters ’ school fees.
“ My husband and I have just bought a house, that ’ s where all my money is in, ” says Amirthalinga.
Although she earned 3,000 Singapore dollars each month (about 1,1,730 euros) as administrators and her husband works, monthly family income is not enough, she explains.
Indeed, demand in parts of Southeast Asia – where household debt is increasing – is so high that ValueMax, where it exchanged, became the third deposit house listed on the Singaporean Stock Exchange this week.
Gdging jewellery is not only a quick way to get money – $1,300 Singapore in the case of Janani Amirthalinga – but also almost as cheap as an unsecured bank loan.
Typically, deposit houses in Singapore require an effective annual interest rate of 17%, just above the 15.4% required by United Overseas Bank, a local lender with a branch in the same shopping mall.
Deposit houses, however, have the advantage that there is no need to check creditworthiness or proof of income, which is why loans are possible more quickly than in the case of banks.
As a result, millions of people in the region turn to deposit houses, as families feel the pressure of rising the cost of living and an increase in household and consumer debt.
After five years of robust growth since the global financial crisis and cheap credit, owing to loose fiscal policies in developed economies, families with lower- and middle-income seek deposit houses to make up the difference as the economy falters.
This week, the credit rating agency Standard & Poor's growing household debt, mainly through rising mortgages, described it as a risk factor for the creditworthiness of Asian banks.
The Agency estimates that Malaysia, Thailand and Singapore have the highest household debt in Asia in relation to gross domestic product.
Malaysia is at the top of the list, at 80% of GDP, with an increase of 60% as recently as 2008.
Economists are also concerned about the high level of consumer debt in Thailand, which narrowly emerged from a technical recession this week.
On Thursday, the data showed a continuing weakness in exports and a slowdown in consumer demand.
“ Ultimately, this means that, as costs rise, people in the middle to lower segment (the income scale) will try to supplement their incomes wherever possible, ” says Song Seng Wun, economist at CIMB, a Malaysian bank.
Historical highs in gold prices over the past two years have exacerbated the trend to pledge personal items, as people take advantage of the opportunity to turn family jewellery into cash.
In Singapore, about 70% of the pledged objects in the 200 deposit houses in the city are gold.
People say, “ The price of gold looks good, let us mortgage grandmother ’ s gold chain, and bring it back next month. ”
EasyMoney, the largest Thai Pfandhouse operator, has seen a 20% increase in customers in recent months in its branches.
Growth in deposit is so strong that ValueMax, operator of the Bendemeer branch and 15 others in Singapore, wants to expand not only to neighboring Malaysia – where the company operates four houses – but also outside Asia, says Yeah Lee Ching, Managing Director of ValueMax.
The company finances this at 60% of the $66 million Singapore dollars it earned this week with the Singapore IPO.
While some lenders had caught in the crossfire of high interest rates, Yeah says that deposit houses would not only offer more favorable interest rates than other lenders, but would not directly increase debt debt.
“ Customers borent items they already own, and liquefying personal valuables does not increase household debt, ” she explains.
The mortgage lending business is increasingly accepted by society as short-term, secured financing.
Nor are not all people who use bonds in financial trouble.
Rich people from Singapore also come to the branches of ValueMax to mortgage gold bars and Rolex watches, for which they receive up to 60% of the purchase price in cash.
Customers from all social backgrounds come to us.
“ These include wealthy who borrow for a business or investment in the short run, or small businesses who have to bridge cash flow bottlenecks, ” says Yeah.
Sometimes they need money very quickly.
