But passengers should not expect these changes implemented immediately.
At a press conference, FAA staff member Michael Huerta explained how quickly they were implemented depended on the airline airline.
The airlines must prove to the FAA that aircraft comply with the new guidelines and that they have updated the training manuals of air crew and the rules on the storage of equipment in accordance with the new rules.
The FAA stated that it had already received plans from some airlines to increase the use of portable electronic equipment in aircraft.
Among these airlines were Delta and JetBlue.
“ Depending on the state of the plan, we could approve the enhanced use of electronic devices very soon, ” the FAA announced.
At present, passengers have to turn off smartphones, tablets and other devices when the aircraft doors are closed.
You will not be allowed to take off again until the aircraft has reached a height of three kilometres and the captain has given the green light.
When entering the landing, passengers must switch them off again and not take them back before the aircraft has landed.
Under the new directives, airlines whose aircraft are protected against electronic disruptions could allow their passengers to use the equipment on take-off, landing and on the roller field, the FAA explained.
Most of the new aircraft and other aircraft that have been converted to use Wi-Fi at higher altitudes should meet the criteria.
Laura Glading, president of the professional association of professional flight attendants, welcomed the changes.
“ If the new regulation is implemented safely – and we are working closely with the airline in this regard – it will benefit both sides, ” Glading commented.
Quite honestly, we are tired of having to feel watchdogs on this issue.
Nevertheless, Internet connections for surfing, exchanging e-mails, text messages, or downloading data of less than three kilometers remained prohibited, the authority explained.
Passengers are asked to fly to smartphones, tablets and other devices.
So still not “ Words With Friends, ” the Scrabble like online game that actor Alec Baldwin played on his smartphone in 2011, when he had to leave a jet from American Airlines because he refused to turn off the device while the plane was parked at the boarding gate.
And heavier equipment, such as laptops, must continue to be stored, because there is a risk of injury here if they fly through the cabin.
Mobile phone calls during the flight will also remain prohibited.
The regulatory competence for telephone calls lies with the Federal Communications Commission (FCC), not the FAA.
FAA may lift a ban on certain electronic devices at take-off and landing
Last month, Mark Rosenker of the National Transportation Safety Board, on CBS News, said that mobile phones are still regarded as a risk.
“ Mobile phones really are a problem, not only because they could potentially disrupt navigation devices, but also because we at the FCC know that aerial transmission can also disrupt transmitters, ” Rosenker says.
An industry advisory committee set up by the FAA to examine this issue recommended last month that the government allow ise wider use of personal electronic equipment.
In recent years, pressure has increased on FAA to ease restrictions on use.
Critics like Missouri Democratic Senator Claire McCaskill argue that there are no valid safety reasons for the ban.
Restrictions are also becoming increasingly difficult to enforce because the use of equipment has become ubiquitous.
Some studies say that up to one third of passengers forget about or ignore the shutdown.
The FAA began to restrict the use of electronic equipment by passengers in 1966, as reports of disruption to navigation and communications equipment by passenger FM radios became known, which were the latest technological trends at the time.
New aircraft are far more dependent on electrical systems than previous generations of aircraft, but they are also designed and approved by the FAA in such a way that they do not mind electronic interference.
Airlines have been providing Wi-Fi to passengers for several years when the height of the flight is reached.
The aircraft adapted to Wi-Fi systems are also more insensitive to interferences.
Mr Huerta said, the vast majority of passenger aircraft should be suitable for greater use of electronic equipment in accordance with the new guidelines.
Today ’ s electronic devices generally emit far less radio radiation than previous generations.
E-readers, for example, only emit minimal radiation if you flip over.
But when downloading or sending data, the transfer values are stronger.
Advocates of loosening restrictions on passenger use of equipment include Amazon.com.
In 2011, company employees invited a passenger aircraft full of Kindle e-readers and took a test flight to identify problems, but were unable to identify any.
Members of the FAA Advisory Committee expressed mixed feelings about the risk of using equipment.
Douglas Kidd of the National Association of Airline Passengers said that he believed that the disruption caused by the equipment was real, even if the risk was minimal.
Other members of the committee have said that there are only a few reports from pilots in favour of disbing aircraft systems, most of which are very old.
However, the committee recommended to the FAA that pilots should be allowed to order equipment switched off by passengers when landing instruments in poor visibility.
A group from the travel industry welcomed the amendments and described them as a sensible adaptation for travellers, who would now be fully equipped with technology.
“ We are pleased that the FAA recognizes that a pleasant passenger experience does not conflict with safety, ” said Roger Dow, CEO of the U.S. Travel Association.
