Scientists have been able to shed more light on the connection between a dog ’ s tail eding and its mood.
Previous research had shown that happy dogs waving the tail more to the right (from the dog's point of view), while in nervous dogs it was the left.
But now scientists say that other dogs can perceive and respond to these subtle differences.
Professor Georgio Vallortigara, a neuroscientist at Trento University, said, “ Man is well aware that the left and right half of the brain react differently to stimulus that arouses positive or negative emotions. ”
Here we have tried to look at this in the case of other species.
He also noticed that in dogs as well as in humans, the right half of the brain was responsible for the movement of the left and vice versa, and that the two hemispheres played different roles in emotions.
To learn more about how dogs react to the lateral swings of their species, the researchers supervised the animals while watched the films of other dogs.
They measured the four-legged heart rate and analyzed the behavior.
We will probably soon understand why the tail is moving in one direction.
Professor Vallortigara said, “ We have shown dogs films with dogs – either a faithful version to nature or a silhouette to eliminate distracting other aspects, and we have been able to control the tail movement more left or right. ”
When the animals saw how an otherwise expressive dog moved the tail to the right (from the point of view of the waving dog), they remained completely relaxed.
But if the tail tendency was mainly left (again from the perspective of the wwing dog), their heart rate rose and they looked restless.
According to Professor Vallortigara, dogs do not deliberately communicate with each other through these movements.
He is convinced that the dogs have learned from experience which movements they should and should not be concerned about.
He said, “ If you have different encounters with other dogs, and swallowing with the tail in one direction is more linked to friendly behavior, and the right produces rather less friendly behavior, you will react on the basis of those experiences. ”
Researchers say that the findings could help dog owners, vets, and trainers to gain a better understanding of their animal ’ s emotions.
John Bradshaw, an expert on dog behaviour and hospitality at the Faculty of Veterinary Medicetrics at the University of Bristol, said that this was not the first study to examine whether the left and the right were important for dogs.
Last year, a team from the University of Lincoln found out that dogs turn their heads to the left when they look at an aggressive dog, and to the right when it is a satisfied dog.
Another research at the University of Victoria in Canada said: “ Dogs are more likely to approach a robot dog when his “ tail ” wings left, not right, rather than restled – the other way around than the Italian study. ”
According to him, the differences could stem from the fact that the dogs did not interpret the animals as dogs in the films or robot dogs in the various studies.
A study of how dogs react to real dogs could help, he explained.
“ While there is considerable evidence for many different mammals that the two halves of the brain are used for different purposes, many of the details still need to be determined – and dogs are no exception, ” Bradshaw said.
Since their behaviour is easy to record, it will probably not be long before we understand why the tail sometimes moves in one direction, sometimes in the other.
