Tourism: Descent to the Romans
At a length of about 120 metres, a sewage canal from the Roman period has been preserved below Cologne.
Visitors to Cologne will not miss the cathedral.
Around 157 metres the two towers rise into the sky, making it the second highest church building in Europe.
Few visitors, however, who admire the two delicate church towers, imagine that there is also a lot to discover beneath the cathedral.
Rainer Schulze is an expert in the Cologne underworld.
Meeting point for his guided tours is the Köln-Tourismus Service Centre directly at the cathedral.
The tour starts quite unspectacularly: " We start in the underground car park, " says Schulze.
In the 1970s, the fathers of the city wanted a city that was appropriate for cars, and therefore, of the remains of the old city wall, only what was not too big stopped.
As a result, most users of the multi-storey car park are now rushing past the Roman remains and only parking their cars.
However, if you take a closer look, you will find an archaeological site in the D2 parking deck, which is separated by metal grids.
You can see ruins, about five metre high, made of hand-made stones.
" They are remains of the Roman city wall built in the second half of the first century, " Schulze says.
Before it comes back to light, Schulze lets the participants on the upper level of the park take a look at a sinister shaft, which is 15 metres deep.
This is the well of the old cathedral, which, unfortunately, is scarcely noticed.
Nearby stop of the tour is the pretorium, and here the participants descend again into the depths.
We are witnessing here the seat of the once most powerful man north of the Alps, the preacher the CCAA.
A visitor would like to know what CCAA means.
The abbreviation stands for " Colonia Claudia Ara Agrippinensium ", which means " means " the city of Roman law and the city of the Agrippines, founded under Emperor Claudius on the site of the altar for the cult of the emperor.
And the pretorium is the former palace of governors, the center of power of the Roman Empire on the Rhine.
A tunnel leads from the anteroom of the exhibition to the Roman sewage channel, which has been preserved here at about 120 metres in length.
" You can walk a bit along the so called Cloaca Maxima if you like, " Schulze encourages guests.
Schulze still has a surprise.
After getting the key at the checkout, it leads the group to a 16 meter deep walkable shaft.
" We are now in Mikwe, a ritual Jewish bath, " he explains.
The Jewish community built its bath deep into the ground in order to obtain the groundwater that was essential for the ritual washing.
To this day, at the lower end of the Mikwe, whose origins date back to the eighth century, different water levels can be read through changing levels of the Rhine.
The Mikwe will be part of an archeological area on the Town Hall Square, for which construction work is due to begin shortly.
It will, however, be a few more years before completion.
